 and the violence of cultural aestheticisation; and racialicity attends to the politics of recognition and the technologies of enfleshment at the systemic edge of life and nonlife.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aWhite peoplexRace identityxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aaffect studies.  acapitalism.  acritical race studies.  acritical whiteness studies.  afragility.  amedieval Christianity.  aperiodisation.  aprecarity.  asubjectivity.1 aKao, Wan-Chuan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2024 eBook-Packagez9783111332345oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614581940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526145819423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526145819/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2024